Creating images with R

with a little bit of magick

2023-03-07

My meme

This meme is a recreation of the “Kid named finger” meme using R, It features Mike Ehrmantraut from the series Breaking Bad, nothing in the meme is new or original.

library(magick)

# Creates a white bar above the image for the caption
meme_caption <- image_blank(width = 500,
            height = 100,
            color = "#ffffff") %>%
  image_annotate(text = "Teacher: Alright class, today\nwe're gonna finger paint",
                 color = "#000000",
                 size = 40)

# Pulls an image from an url and puts a second caption in the image
mike_image <- image_read("https://vignette.wikia.nocookie.net/breakingbad/images/8/8d/BCS_S3_MikeEhrmantraut.jpg/revision/latest?cb=20170327185046") %>%
  image_scale(500) %>%
  image_annotate(text = "   KID NAMED FINGER",
                 color = "#ffffff",
                 size = 60,
                 font = "Impact")

# Combines the caption and the image
meme_vector <- c(meme_caption, mike_image)

# Stacks the images vertically
meme <- image_append(meme_vector, stack = TRUE)

# Saves the meme as an png
image_write(meme, "kidfinger.png")

My animated GIF

This animated GIF is similar to the calming GIF in lab 1B, Instead of counting from 1 through 4, I used the words ‘This is a GIF’. I have opted to not use the morph function as I think it doesn’t look very good in this GIF.

library(magick)

# creating the frames for the gif
frame1 <- image_blank(color = "white", width = 500, height = 500) %>%
  image_annotate(text = "This", size = 100, gravity = "center")

frame2 <- image_blank(color = "white", width = 500, height = 500) %>%
  image_annotate(text = "Is", size = 100, gravity = "center")

frame3 <- image_blank(color = "white", width = 500, height = 500) %>%
  image_annotate(text = "A", size = 100, gravity = "center")

frame4 <- image_blank(color = "white", width = 500, height = 500) %>%
  image_annotate(text = "GIF", size = 100, gravity = "center")

# putting the frames in order using a vector
frames <- c(frame1, frame2, frame3, frame4)

# creating an animation
GIF <- image_animate(frames, fps = 1)

# saves the animation as a gif
image_write(GIF, "animation.gif")
